            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "Are Black Sarees Bad Luck or Bold Fashion? Let’s Talk About It.",
            "text": "<p>Let’s get one thing straight — <strong>black is not a curse</strong>. It’s a color. A powerful, unapologetic, timeless color. So why is it that in many Indian households, black sarees are still met with furrowed brows, whispered warnings, or outright bans at weddings, poojas, and festivals?</p><p><strong>\"Don't wear black to a wedding.\"<br/></strong> <strong>\"Black brings bad luck.\"<br/></strong> <strong>\"It attracts negative energy.\"</strong></p><p>Sound familiar? It’s 2025, and women still hear these lines — especially when reaching for a black saree. But here’s the truth: <strong>black is not unlucky — it's unstoppable</strong>.</p><h2>The Taboo Behind the Thread</h2><p>Traditionally, black in Indian culture has been associated with sorrow, mourning, and negativity. It’s considered inauspicious for spiritual ceremonies or moments of celebration. The superstition goes even deeper — black is thought to absorb the <strong>nazar</strong>, or evil eye. So, wearing it during life’s most sacred events is seen as an invitation for misfortune.</p><p>Because of this, <strong>black sarees are often sidelined</strong> during weddings, temple visits, and festivals. They’re replaced with reds, yellows, whites — anything but black.</p><p>But here’s the kicker — <strong>is this tradition or just fear dressed up as culture?</strong></p><p>Because organza doesn’t flow. It <strong>commands</strong>.<br/><br/></p>",
